translation of the liability balance at the balance sheet rate and restructuring expense translated at the weighted-average rate of exchange for the applicable period.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Retail Store Closings</font> </p> <p style="margin:4.5pt 0pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As mentioned above, the Company plans to close 75 to 100 retail locations around the globe. As such, we expect to incur certain exit costs specific to store closures including operating lease termination costs, rent obligations for leased facilities, net of expected sublease income, and other expenses in association with this plan. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nine</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, we clos</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed 26 and 36 co</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">mpany-operated </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">retail locations, respectively, which were not scheduled to close until future periods and were selected for closure by management based on historical and projected profitability levels, relocation plans, and other factor</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s. As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, we recorded a liability of appro</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$1.1</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million rela</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ted to these locations in accrued restructuring on the condensed consolidated balance sh</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">eet. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The calculation of accrued store closing reserves primarily includes future minimum lease payments from the date of closure to the end of the remaining lease term, net of contractual or estimated sublease income. We record the liability at fair value in the period in which the store is closed.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 13895000 12398000 2255000 9806000 337000 7585000 4064000 </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">15</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. OPERATING SEGMENTS &amp; GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">W</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e have </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">four</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> reportable operating segments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> based on the geographic nature of our operations</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">: Americas,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Asia Pacific, Japan and Europe. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We also have an &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category which aggregates insignificant operating segments that do not meet the reportable threshold and represent manufacturing o</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">perations located in Mexico, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Italy</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and Asia. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The composition of our reportable operating segments is consistent with that used by our </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Chief Operating Decision Maker (&#x201C;CODM&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to evaluate performance and allocate resources.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Each of our reportable operating segments derives its revenues from the sale of footwear, apparel and accessories to external customers</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as well as intersegment sales</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. Revenues of the &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category are primaril</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">y made up of intersegment sales</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The remaining revenues for the &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; represent non-footwear produ</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ct sales to external customers. Intersegment sales are not included in the measurement of segment operating income or regularly reviewed by the CODM and are eliminated when deriving total consolidated revenues.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The primary </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">financial </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">measure utilized by the CODM to evaluate performance and allocate resources is segment operating income. Segment performance evaluation is based primarily on segment results without allocating corporate expenses, or indirect general, ad</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ministrative and other expenses. Segment profits or losses of our reportable operating segments include adjustments to eliminate intersegment profit or losses on intersegment sales. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As such, reconciling items for segment operating income represent unallocated corporate and other expenses as well as intersegment eliminations. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Segment assets consist of cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable and inventory</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as these balances are regularly reviewed by the CODM</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 12pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table sets forth information related to our reportable operating business segments during the </font><font style="display: inline;">three</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">nine</font><font style="display: inline;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">2013</font><font style="display: inline;">:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: Corporate assets primarily consist of cash and equivalents which increased predominately due to net cash proceeds from our investment with Blackstone. See Note 13 - Series A Preferred Stock for further details regarding the preferred share offering. Includes a corporate component consisting primarily of corporate support and administrative functions, costs associated with share-based compensation, research and development, brand marketing, legal, depreciation and amortization of corporate and other assets not allocated to operating segments and costs of the same nature related to certain corporate holding companies. Includes $2.4 million and $1.9 million of accumulated amortization of software held under a capital lease as of September 30, 2014 and December 31, 2013, respectively, which is amortized using the straight-line method over the useful life. Includes $4.1 million of software held under a capital lease classified as capitalized software as of September 30, 2014 and December 31, 2013. Minimum rentals include all lease payments as well as fixed and variable common area maintenance (CAM), parking and storage fees, which were approximately $2.3 million and $2.5 million during the three months ended September 30, 2014 and 2013, respectively, and $7.3 million and $7.4 million during the nine months ended September 30, 2014 and 2013, respectively. The amounts in Other consist of various accrued expenses and no individual item accounted for more than 5% of the total balance at September 30, 2014 or December 31, 2013. The amounts in Other consist of various asset impairment charges prompted by the aforementioned restructuring plan, legal fees and facility maintenance fees. Includes $0.1 million and $0.1 million of certain equipment held under capital leases and classified as equipment as of September 30, 2014 and December 31, 2013, respectively. Adjustments relate to differences resulting from the translation of the liability balance at the balance sheet rate and restructuring expense translated at the weighted-average rate of exchange for the applicable period. The RSAs vested during the three and nine months ended September 30, 2014 and 2013 consisted entirely of time-based awards. The RSUs vested during the three months ended September 30, 2014 and 2013 consisted entirely of time-based awards. The RSUs vested during the nine months ended September 30, 2014 consisted of 473,108 of time-based awards and 30,946 of performance-based awards. The RSUs vested during the nine months ended September 30, 2013 consisted of 242,927 of time-based awards and 52,288 of performance-based awards.
